<% content_for :sign_in do %>
<% #========================================================================= %>
<h2>Overview</h2>

<p>
  You can sign up or sign in using either an
  <a href="http://openid.net/">OpenID</a> or an e-mail address and password.
</p>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>
      An OpenID is a globally unique way for you to identify yourself to any
      OpenID-aware web site. You don't create a new password for every
      new site; you have just one, for your account with your OpenID
      <em>provider.</em> See
      <%= auto_link( 'http://openid.net/get-an-openid/' ) %> for details.
    </p>
  </li>
  
  <li>
    <p>
      You might find OpenID confusing or find it hard to choose a provider.
      If having trouble, use a password instead. It means you have yet another
      password to remember and keep secure, but it is a familiar way to work.
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>
  
<h2>Signing up</h2>

<p>
  Tell your system administrator your e-mail address and either tell them
  your OpenID, or that you want to use a password. They will add you to the
  system and let you know when it's ready, giving you a temporary one-off
  password if you are using that kind of account. You can then sign in.
</p>

<h2>Signing in</h2>

<ul>
  <li>
    <p>
      If using OpenID, just enter the ID and nothing else into the
      <%= link_to "sign-in form", signin_path() %>. You will probably
      get taken to your provider's web site to verify the sign-in the
      first time around.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <p>
      Otherwise, enter your e-mail address and the temporary one-off
      password into the <%= link_to "sign-in form", signin_path() %>. You
      will be asked to change the password to something only you know. Use
      this for sign-in thereafter. If you forget the password, you will have
      to ask the administrator to reset it.
    </p>
  </li>
</ul>

<h2>A note on OpenID longevity</h2>

<p>
  OpenIDs are kept for life. Your provider will let you delete your OpenID
  account to invalidate it, but the ID is remembered so that nobody can ever
  use it again. Nobody can impersonate you, either accidentally or maliciously,
  by choosing your old ID.
</p>

<p>
  Please visit the OpenID web site at <%= auto_link( 'http://openid.net/' ) %>
  for more information.
</p>
<% #========================================================================= %>
<% end %>
